Let $$a = \widehat i + \widehat j + \widehat k$$ and $$b = 2\widehat i + 3\widehat j - \widehat k$$<br><br>Clearly, the vector which is orthogonal to both the vectors, is <br><br>$$a \times b = \left| {\matrix{
   {\widehat i} &amp; {\widehat j} &amp; {\widehat k}  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   2 &amp; 3 &amp; { - 1}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = \widehat i( - 1 - 3) - \widehat j( - 1 - 2) + \widehat k(3 - 2)$$<br><br>$$ =  - 4\widehat i + 3\widehat j + \widehat k$$<br><br>Now, required vector = Unit vector along a $$\times$$ b<br><br>$$ = {{ - 4\widehat i + 3\widehat j + \widehat k} \over {\sqrt {{{( - 4)}^2} + {{(3)}^2} + {1^2}} }} = {{ - 4\widehat i + 3\widehat j + \widehat k} \over {\sqrt {26} }}$$

Given, $$f(x) = \left| {\matrix{
   {{x^3}} &amp; {\sin x} &amp; {\cos x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>where, p is a constant.<br><br>On differentiating both sides w.r.t. x, we get<br><br>$$f'(x) = \left| {\matrix{
   {3{x^2}} &amp; {\cos x} &amp; { - \sin x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| + \left| {\matrix{
   {{x^3}} &amp; {\sin x} &amp; {\cos x}  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| + \left| {\matrix{
   {{x^3}} &amp; {\sin x} &amp; {\cos x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(x) = \left| {\matrix{
   {3{x^2}} &amp; {\cos x} &amp; { - \sin x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| + 0 + 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(0) = \left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; {\cos 0} &amp; { - \sin 0}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(0) = \left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = ( - 1)(6{p^3} - 0)$$<br><br>$$ =  - 6{p^3}$$

From question 18,<br><br>$$f'(x) = \left| {\matrix{
   {3{x^2}} &amp; {\cos x} &amp; { - \sin x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>Again, differentiating both sides, w.r.t. x, we get<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f''(x) = \left| {\matrix{
   {6x} &amp; { - \sin x} &amp; { - \cos x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| + \left| {\matrix{
   {3{x^2}} &amp; {\cos x} &amp; { - \sin x}  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| + \left| {\matrix{
   {3{x^2}} &amp; {\cos x} &amp; { - \sin x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f''(x) = \left| {\matrix{
   {6x} &amp; { - \sin x} &amp; { - \cos x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| + 0 + 0$$<br><br>Since, we have $$f''(0) = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f''(0) = \left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; { - \sin 0} &amp; {\cos 0}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow 6{p^2} + p = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow p(6p + 1) = 0$$<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ p = 0 or 6p + 1 = 0<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ p = 0 or p = $$ - {1 \over 6}$$ $$\Rightarrow$$ p = $$ - {1 \over 6}$$ or 0

