Given,<br><br>$$f(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {2x + 1,} &amp; { - 3 &lt; x &lt;  - 2}  \cr 
   {x - 1,} &amp; { - 2 \le x &lt; 0}  \cr 
   {x + 2,} &amp; {0 \le x &lt; 1}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>Here, $$f( - {2^ - }) = 2( - 2) + 1 =  - 3$$<br><br>$$f( - {2^ + }) =  - 2 - 1 =  - 3$$<br><br>Here, $$f( - {2^ - }) = f( - {2^ + })$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ f(x) is continuous t x = $$-$$2<br><br>and, $$f({0^ - }) = (0 - 1) =  - 1$$<br><br>$$f({0^ + }) = 0 + 2 = 0$$<br><br>Here, $$f({0^ - }) \ne f({0^ + })$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ f(x) is discontinuous at x = 0<br><br>$$\therefore$$ f(x) is discontinuous at x = 0<br><br>but continuous at every point.

Given,<br><br>$$f(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {3{x^2} + 12x - 1,} &amp; { - 1 \le x \le 2}  \cr 
   {37 - x,} &amp; {2 &lt; x \le 3}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>$$\because$$ 3x<sup>2</sup> + 12x $$-$$ 1 = 3(x<sup>2</sup> + 4x + 4) $$-$$ 12 $$-$$ 1 = 3(x + 2)<sup>2</sup> $$-$$ 13<br><br>Now, we can draw graph of f(x) in which ($$-$$2, $$-$$13) is vertex of 3x<sup>2</sup> + 12x $$-$$ 1<br><br><img src="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1l1fnzpz4/be7fb08c-07b3-433f-a183-699d1e8145b1/6a6f1400-b14f-11ec-a398-7719bab53b26/file-1l1fnzpz5.png?format=png" data-orsrc="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1l1fnzpz4/be7fb08c-07b3-433f-a183-699d1e8145b1/6a6f1400-b14f-11ec-a398-7719bab53b26/file-1l1fnzpz5.png" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-height:40vh" alt="NDA 2016 Paper 2 Mathematics - Application of Derivatives Question 50 English Explanation"><br>$$\because$$ Graph of f(x) does not break at x = 2.<br><br>$$\therefore$$ f(x) is continuous at x = 2.<br><br>$$\because$$ From graph, f(x) attains maximum value at x = 2, which is 35.<br><br>Since, graph of f(x) makes sharp edge at x = 2.<br><br>$$\therefore$$ f(x) is not differentiable at x = 2.

