 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ x = 0<br><br>hence, x = 0 is a solution.

Given, $$E(\theta ) = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; {\sin \theta }  \cr 
   { - \sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta }  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$E(\alpha ) = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \alpha } &amp; {\sin \alpha }  \cr 
   { - \sin \alpha } &amp; {\cos \alpha }  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>and $$E(\beta ) = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \beta } &amp; {\sin \beta }  \cr 
   { - \sin \beta } &amp; {\cos \beta }  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$E(\alpha )E(\beta ) = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \alpha } &amp; {\sin \alpha }  \cr 
   { - \sin \alpha } &amp; {\cos \alpha }  \cr 

 } } \right]\left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \beta } &amp; {\sin \beta }  \cr 
   { - \sin \beta } &amp; {\cos \beta }  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \alpha .\cos \beta  - \sin \alpha .\sin \beta } &amp; { - \sin \alpha .\cos \beta  - \sin \beta .\cos \alpha }  \cr 
   {\cos \alpha .\sin \beta  + \sin \alpha .\cos \beta } &amp; { - \sin \alpha .\sin \beta  + \cos \alpha .\cos \beta }  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$ = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos (\alpha  + \beta )} &amp; {\sin (\alpha  + \beta )}  \cr 
   { - \sin (\alpha  + \beta )} &amp; {\cos (\alpha  + \beta )}  \cr 

 } } \right] = E(\alpha  + \beta )$$
